<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · What we do</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A reach-in cooler at 50°F at 11 AM means lunch service starts in 30 minutes with food already out of FDA spec.</h2>

    <p>Our techs service the upright reach-in coolers in commercial kitchens across SoCal: single-door, double-door, triple-door. All major brands. EPA 608 Universal certified. Phones answered 24/7.</p>

    <p>The most common reach-in models we see in LA: True T-23 (single-door), True T-49 (double-door, the most popular reach-in in industry), True T-72 (triple-door), Turbo Air M3R (their full reach-in line), Traulsen G Series and R Series (premium American), Beverage-Air HR1 and HR2 (Ali Group), Continental CRA, Hoshizaki commercial line, Victory, Migali, Norlake, Avantco.</p>

    <p>BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. Eight branches across SoCal means tech response time stays tight. Parent context: <a href="/commercial/refrigeration/">commercial refrigeration repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical failures, by frequency</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Eight failure modes account for nearly every reach-in service call we run.</h2>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor seizure (year 4 to 6).</strong> The 1,800 to 3,000 RPM motor that pulls air through the condenser coil. Runs 24/7. Dust, kitchen grease, fryer particulate eat motors fast. When it stops, the condensing unit overheats and cooler temp climbs. Replacement $280 to $500 depending on motor size and brand.</li>
      <li><strong>Evaporator fan motor failure (year 5 to 7).</strong> The fan inside the cabinet that circulates cold air over the food. When it dies, refrigerant cycles normally but cold air doesn't reach the food. Temp at the thermostat sensor reads cold while the food at the door warms up. Replacement $260 to $450.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost timer or defrost board issue.</strong> Electromechanical Paragon timers (legacy True, Turbo Air, Beverage-Air) versus modern defrost boards (newer units). Stuck-in-defrost is the most common defrost failure: heater stays on past timer cycle, ice melts, refreezes when cycle ends, restricts evap airflow. Replacement timer $200 to $340, defrost board $380 to $620.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket compression.</strong> Magnetic gaskets on commercial reach-ins compress flat at the hinge side first (door gravity). Replacement at year 3 to 5 for heavy-use restaurants (50 to 200 cycles per day). $180 to $340 per door installed.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor capacitor or start relay failure.</strong> Electrical components on the compressor. Capacitor swelling or relay pitting prevents compressor start. Diagnostic with multimeter. $200 to $340 part plus labor.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant slow leak.</strong> EPA 608 requires leak repair before recharge. We use electronic leak detector or UV dye, identify leak point (typically at a brazed joint or coil seam), pump down, repair, evacuate to 500 microns, recharge to nameplate spec. $600 to $1,400 depending on charge size.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermostat calibration drift.</strong> At 5+ years, thermostats drift, reading 38°F at sensor while food at 44°F. Replacement or recalibration. $200 to $360.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor failure (year 8 to 15).</strong> Mechanical wear. Cost-vs-replacement decision threshold here. Often a 10-year-old reach-in with compressor failure is a replace conversation, not a repair conversation.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 BRAND NOTES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Brand-specific notes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Eight brands cover roughly 90% of reach-in calls in SoCal.</h2>

    <p><strong>True Manufacturing</strong>: Trulaske family-owned (Missouri). Independent. T-23 / T-49 / T-72 most common. Excellent parts availability, 5-day service through True parts network. The T-49F freezer variant shares about 80% of parts with the T-49 cooler.</p>

    <p><strong>Turbo Air</strong>: Korean, US distribution strong. M3R single, MSR-49 double-door, MSR-72 triple. Aggressive pricing, post-2018 quality competitive with True.</p>

    <p><strong>Traulsen</strong>: ITW Food Equipment Group. G Series (mid-tier) and R Series (premium). Higher service ticket but reliability is industry-leading. Common in chain restaurants and hotels.</p>

    <p><strong>Beverage-Air</strong>: Ali Group since around 2005. HR1 single, HR2 double. Mid-premium, common in chain restaurants.</p>

    <p><strong>Continental Refrigerator</strong>: Pittsburgh-based, premium American. CRA series.</p>

    <p><strong>Hoshizaki</strong>: Japanese manufacturer, premium quality reach-ins (separate from their ice machine line).</p>

    <p><strong>Victory, Migali, Norlake, Avantco</strong>: value-tier and mid-tier. Parts available but less stocked locally. Typical 2 to 5 day part turnaround through our distributor network.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real repair stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · True T-49 two-door cooler, 7 years old, R-134a</h3>
      <p>Restaurant on Sunset Blvd. Friday lunch rush, cooler at 51°F. Tech dispatched 22 minutes from West Hollywood branch. Diagnosed: condenser fan motor seized (kitchen grease load on coastal install). Replaced motor (True OEM via True parts), cleaned condenser coil thoroughly. Pulldown to 36°F in 90 minutes. Total: $120 plus $385 part plus 1.5 hours = $580.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Turbo Air M3R47 reach-in, 5 years old</h3>
      <p>Coffee shop. Temp climbing overnight from 38°F to 47°F. Diagnosed: defrost timer stuck-in-defrost cycle. Heater running continuously, ice melted then refroze on evaporator, blocking airflow. Replaced timer, manual defrost cycle, monitored 24 hours. Total: $120 plus $215 timer plus 1.5 hours = $445.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · Beverage-Air HR2-1S two-door cooler, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Bakery. Temp at 44°F, just out of FDA spec. Diagnosed: evaporator fan motor failed. Cold air not circulating. Replaced motor, tested airflow, calibrated thermostat. Total: $120 plus $310 part plus 1 hour = $530.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Santa Monica · Traulsen G20010 single-door, 11 years old</h3>
      <p>Bar. Refrigerant slow leak, owner had been topping off through previous service (illegal under EPA 608). Used UV dye injection, identified leak at evaporator brazed joint. Pumped down, brazed repair, evacuated, recharged R-404A to 14 oz nameplate spec. Total: $120 plus $480 refrigerant plus $620 labor plus leak detection = $1,260. Owner now compliant with EPA 608 leak repair requirement.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · True T-72 triple-door, 12 years old</h3>
      <p>Cafeteria. Compressor not starting. Diagnosed: capacitor swollen, start relay pitted. Replaced capacitor and relay together (always replace as a pair on aged compressors). Tested 6 start cycles, all good. Total: $120 plus $245 parts plus 1 hour = $440.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we do, and what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong> all major reach-in brands and models, single, double, triple door. Cooler and freezer variants. All EPA-permitted refrigerants (R-22 legacy, R-134a, R-404A, R-448A, R-449A, R-507, R-454B, R-290 where applicable per safety codes).</p>

    <p><strong>We don't do:</strong> new reach-in installation (we work with several restaurant equipment installers in SoCal, happy to refer); reach-in disposal and hauling (different trade); refrigerant recovery for end-of-life equipment without subsequent service (we do recovery as part of ongoing service work).</p>

    <p>Knowing the boundary is part of being a real practitioner. Premium restaurants and hospitality operators value contractors who refer specialty work to specialists rather than fake competence.</p>
  </div>
</section>

